{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01RLXc8e74NXSLXVDJwpSqMS","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"OK so `db.adminCommand('ping')` works without auth (it's allowed), but `createUser` requires auth. And there are no users. This seems like a chicken-and-egg problem.\n\nWait, let me check the MongoDB logs again more carefully. The message was \"no users configured in admin.system.users, allowing localhost access\" - that was logged at startup time. But then subsequent operations requiring auth failed. Could it be that some users were created in between (maybe via another init process we're not aware of)?\n\nActually, let me re-examine. The initial log message was:\n```\n\"note: no users configured in admin.system.users, allowing localhost access\"\n```\n\nThis means when MongoDB started, there were no users, so localhost exception was enabled. But then `createUser requires authentication`. Wait, if localhost exception is enabled, you shouldn't need auth...\n\nOh wait, I think the issue is that MongoDB's localhost exception requires connecting directly from localhost without specifying auth, AND the command must be the FIRST connection. Once MongoDB has been connected to via the readinessProbe, the localhost exception might be consumed.\n\nActually no, the localhost exception in MongoDB persists until at least one user has been created. It doesn't get consumed by a single connection.\n\nLet me try a different approach - connect via mongosh without any credentials but explicitly to see if that bypasses the auth requirement.\n```","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":587,"cache_read_input_tokens":39024,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":587},"output_tokens":25,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"