{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01Tk4u4jbEt1jaU125KFmDpD","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The localhost exception isn't working. This is strange. Let me check if there's a way to see the current users. Perhaps some init script ran and created users. Let me look at the log more carefully, particularly the time sequence.\n\nActually wait - the log says:\n1. \"no users configured in admin.system.users, allowing localhost access\" at 02:44:07 (startup)\n2. Then various \"Checking authorization failed\" messages for atlascli\n\nBut these authorization failures are for commands that require auth. The localhost exception allows you to do certain things without auth, but only from localhost. The readinessProbe is running from inside the container, so that would be localhost...\n \nHmm, but `createUser` also requires auth even with the localhost exception. The MongoDB docs mention that the localhost exception lets you connect as if there's no auth, but the connection needs to come from `127.0.0.1` specifically. When using `kubectl exec`, the connection might be coming from a different IP address, which would bypass the exception. Let me try connecting explicitly through `127.0.0.1` to see if that makes a difference.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":510,"cache_read_input_tokens":39611,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":510},"output_tokens":28,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"1124b000-7cc4-4891-aa45-2cfbe3690053","uuid":"e5ad2019-31da-40e1-a02a-e174f0eebb68","request_id":"req_011CcgFtBRy66xyGsHiivBHm"}
